# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1919-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1882 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was the first season for the team as a member of the American Association.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] This team took the nickname from the previous National League team that played during 1876–1879, but was otherwise unrelated.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings (sometimes called the "Reds") won the first American Association championship this season.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the season began, the Red Stockings named catcher Pop Snyder as the player-manager.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder spent the 1881 season with the Boston Red Caps of the National League, hitting .228 with 16 RBI.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed some familiar players, as Will White and Hick Carpenter spent time with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] White saw limited action with the Detroit Wolverines, while Carpenter hit .216 with two home runs and 31 RBI with the Worcester Worcesters during the 1881 season.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Carpenter had a breakout season, as he led the AA with 67 RBI and 120 hits, and led the Red Stockings with a .342 batting average.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Snyder hit .291 with a homer and 50 RBI, while Joe Sommer hit .288 with a homer, 29 RBI and a team high 82 runs, while leading the league with 354 at-bats.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White returned to his 1879 form, as he led the AA with 40 wins, while posting a 1.54 ERA in 480 innings pitched.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings lost their first ever game, as the Pittsburgh Alleghenys defeated Cincinnati 10–9 at Bank Street Grounds.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a record of 8–9 record in their first 17 games, sitting in fourth place.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a 10-game winning streak and rose to first place in the American Association.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati stayed hot for the rest of the season, finishing with a 55–25 record and winning the American Association pennant, 11.5 games ahead of the second place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1919-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1883 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished third in the American Association with a record of 61–37, 5 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings came into the 1883 season looking to repeat as American Association Champions, as they had a league best record of 55–25 in 1882.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the team announced that catcher Pop Snyder would return as player-manager.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also made a big signing, as they signed Charley Jones, who played with the Cincinnati Reds of the National League from 1876–1878.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Jones had not played professional baseball since 1880, when he played for the Boston Red Caps of the NL, after which he was black-balled from professional baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings also signed another former Reds player, John Reilly, who had also last played major league baseball for the Reds in the 1880 season.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the diamond, the Red Stockings were led by Jones, who hit .294 with a team leading ten home runs, as well as a league leading 80 RBI.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Reilly hit a team high .311 with nine homers and 79 RBI.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Will White continued to be the ace of the pitching staff, posting a 43–22 record with 64 complete games and a 2.09 ERA in 577 innings pitched.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started off the season on the right foot, winning their first four games, and had an impressive 11–5 record in their first sixteen ballgames.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they were 3.5 games behind the Athletics.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would continue to play good baseball, and had a 31–23 record.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would then go on to win twelve of their next thirteen games to improve to 43–24.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they only moved up to third place.
[src:1919-world-series/1883-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings would remain in third place for the rest of the season, finishing the year at 61–37, five games behind the Athletics.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1884 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished fifth in the American Association with a record of 68–41, 8 games behind the New York Metropolitans.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were looking to return to their 1882 form, when they won the American Association pennant before falling to third place in 1883.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club named pitcher Will White the player-manager for the 1884 season, taking over for catcher Pop Snyder.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season, although they did sign Tom Mansell, who had split the previous season between the Detroit Wolverines of the National League, and the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns of the AA, hitting .305 with 34 RBI and 45 runs between those two teams.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The club also moved into American Park for the 1884 season.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly was the offensive force on the team, hitting .339 with eleven home runs and 91 RBI, all club highs.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones hit .314 with seven home runs and 71 RBI, along with a team high 117 runs.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, White led the way with a 34–18 record and a 3.32 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati got off to a slow start, as they lost their first game in their new ballpark, 10–9 to the Columbus Buckeyes, and they had a record of 4–5 in their first nine games, before reeling off four wins in a row to stay above the .500 level for the rest of the season.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got red hot, as they eventually had a 28–14 record, only one game out of first place.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] In a three-game series against the Washington Nationals, the Red Stockings outscored their opposition 48–6.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati started to fade as the season continued on, and with their record at 44–27 changed managers, bringing Pop Snyder back as player-manager.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati continued to slump, falling to 10½ games out of first place with a 52–35 record, but then won ten games in a row to climb back to within 4½ games.
[src:1919-world-series/1884-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] It was too little too late though, as Cincinnati finished the season with a 68–41 record, good enough for fifth place, eight games behind the Metropolitans.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1885 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished second in the American Association, 16 games behind the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] During the off-season, the Red Stockings hired O.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Caylor to become the manager of the team, the first time in club history that the club did not have a player-manager.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati also signed Tony Mullane to a contract.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane, who spent the 1884 season with the Toledo Blue Stockings, had a 36–26 record with a 2.52 ERA in 67 starts, striking out 325 batters.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Mullane was suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, as the Blue Stockings and the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons, another team he tried to sign with, folded after the 1884 season, and the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns attempted to reclaim Mullane, as he pitched there in 1883.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Before the Browns could reclaim him, he signed with the Red Stockings.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Frank Fennelly, who the Red Stockings acquired late in the 1884 season from the Washington Nationals, had a breakout season, hitting .273 with ten home runs and a league high 89 RBI.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Charley Jones led the team with a .322 average, and had five home runs and 35 RBI to go along with it, while John Reilly hit .297 with five homers and 60 RBI.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Larry McKeon led the Red Stockings with 20 wins and a 2.86 ERA in 33 starts, while Will White had eighteen wins and a 3.53 ERA in 34 starts.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati began the season very well, putting up an impressive 16–8 record in their first 24 games to sit in second place in the league, two games behind the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then began to slump, as they would win only six of their next sixteen games to slip into third place, seven games behind the Browns.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On July 1, the Red Stockings acquired Jim Keenan and Larry McKeon, who both jumped from the Detroit Wolverines to join Cincinnati.
[src:1919-world-series/1885-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings improved with their new acquisitions in the lineup, as the team eventually moved back into second place, however, they were too far behind the Browns, and Cincinnati finished the season with a 63–49 record, good for second place, however, they were sixteen games out of first.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1886 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings finished in fifth place in the American Association, 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill had a breakout season, hitting .265 with five home runs and a team high 97 RBI, while Bid McPhee hit .268 with a team highs in home runs with eight, stolen bases with 40, and runs with 139.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Fred Lewis had a team high .318 batting average.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Mullane was the ace of the staff, as he had a 33–27 record with a 3.70 ERA in 56 starts, as he struck out 250 batters in 529.2 innings pitched.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were coming off a second-place finish in the 1885 season, which was their highest placing since winning the 1882 American Association pennant.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati was relatively quiet during the off-season; however, Tony Mullane, who had been suspended for the 1885 season for defying his contract, returned and made his Cincinnati debut in 1886.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings started the season off slowly, winning only four of their first twelve games to sit in seventh place.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati would continue to play mediocre baseball, and would be in eighth place with a 24–35 record, 12.5 games out of first place.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings then went on a seven-game winning streak to climb into sixth place to bring their record to 31–35, however, they remained 12.5 games out of first.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team eventually broke over the .500 level, reaching a season best three games over .500 with a 50–47 record.
[src:1919-world-series/1886-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, Cincinnati faded down the stretch, and finished with a losing record for the first time in team history, as they were 65–73, which was good for fifth place 27.5 games behind the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1887 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in second place in the American Association with a record of 81–45, 14 games behind the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Following a horrible 1886 season, in which the Red Stockings finished under .500 for the first time in team history, the team hired Gus Schmelz to become the new manager.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Maroons of the National League in 1886 to a 43–79 record.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] He also managed the Columbus Buckeyes of the American Association in 1883, leading them to a 69–39 record and a second-place finish.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati signed George Tebeau to his first professional contract, and acquired Hugh Nicol from the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Louis Browns in a trade with sent Jack Boyle and $350 to the Browns.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol hit .206 with 19 RBI and 38 stolen bases, as well as scoring 44 runs in 67 games in 1886.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly had a great season, as he hit .306 with a team high ten home runs and had 96 RBI, as well as 50 stolen bases.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Pop Corkhill led the club with a .311 batting average, and his 97 RBI tied him with Frank Fennelly for the team high.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol led the American Association with 138 stolen bases.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, nineteen-year-old Mike Smith emerged as the ace of the staff, as he had a 34–17 record and a league best 2.94 ERA in 52 starts.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Tony Mullane also had a solid season, as he had a 31–17 record with a 3.24 ERA in 48 starts.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings got off to a fast start, winning their first five games, however, Cincinnati lost six of their next seven games to fall to 6–6.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team hovered around the .500 level, as they had a 21–22 record after 43 games, before winning nine of ten to rise up to third place with a 30–23 record.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] After going 3–6 in their next nine games, Cincinnati had a season-high ten-game winning streak.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, they remained in third place, 8.5 games behind the St.
[src:1919-world-series/1887-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings continued to play good baseball for the remainder of the season, as they finished the year in second place with a record of 81–54, fourteen games behind the first-place Browns.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The **1919 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the 1919 season.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The 16th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox against the National League (NL) champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Although most World Series have been of the best-of-seven format, the 1919 World Series was a best-of-nine series (along with 1903, 1920, and 1921).
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The National Baseball Commission decided to try the best-of-nine format partly to increase popularity of the sport and partly to generate more revenue.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The events of the 1919 World Series are often associated with the Black Sox Scandal, in which several members of the Chicago franchise conspired with gamblers, allegedly led by organized crime figure Arnold Rothstein, to throw the series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] This led the various franchise owners to install Kenesaw Mountain Landis as the first Commissioner of Baseball in 1920.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In August 1921, despite being acquitted from criminal charges, eight players from the White Sox were banned from organized baseball for either fixing the series or having knowledge about the fix without alerting the league.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, another player on the team who was not involved in the scandal, was later suspended after holding out for more pay, but was eventually reinstated.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] They were the first players formally banned in the modern era, and, as it turned out, the template for how Landis would wield his authority throughout his tenure.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] On May 12, 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred lifted all permanent bans — including those of the Black Sox players — on the grounds that deceased players pose no threat to the integrity of the game.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The nine players that were once banned by the MLB (most notably Shoeless Joe Jackson and Eddie Cicotte) are now considered eligible for entry into the Baseball Hall of Fame by as early as 2027.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In 1919, the Chicago White Sox, who had won the World Series two years earlier, had the best record in the American League (AL).
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Most of the same players had defeated the New York Giants in the 1917 series, four games to two.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] They had fallen to sixth place in the American League in 1918, largely as a result of losing their best player, Shoeless Joe Jackson, and a few other teammates to World War I service.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The team's owner, Charles Comiskey, fired manager Pants Rowland after the season and replaced him with William "Kid" Gleason, who had played over twenty years in the majors but had never managed before.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The 88–52 White Sox won the American League pennant again in 1919, by 3+1⁄2 games over the Cleveland Indians (world champions the following year).
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Jackson was the unquestioned star of the White Sox.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The left fielder hit .351 that season, fourth in the league and in the AL's top five in slugging percentage, RBI, total bases and base hits.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] He was not the only star in a lineup with hardly a weak spot, as former Philadelphia Athletics superstar leadoff hitter Eddie Collins, one of the greatest second basemen of all time, was still going strong in his early thirties, hitting .319 with a .400 on-base percentage.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Right fielder Nemo Leibold hit .302 with 81 runs scored.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] First baseman Chick Gandil hit .290, third baseman Buck Weaver .296, and center fielder Oscar "Hap" Felsch hit .275 and tied Jackson for the team lead in home runs with only seven (as the dead-ball era was coming to a close).
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Even typical "good field, no hit" catcher Ray Schalk hit .282 that year, and shortstop Swede Risberg was not an automatic out with the .256 average and 38 RBI.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Gleason's bench contained two impressive hitters, outfielder Shano Collins and infielder Fred McMullin, both veterans of the 1917 series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Eddie Cicotte recorded a 29–7 record, leading the league in wins and ranking second in earned run average to Walter Johnson.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Claude "Lefty" Williams finished with a 23–11 record and a 2.64 ERA.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr started 17 games and recorded a 13–7 record with a 2.88 ERA.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Urban "Red" Faber had an 11–9 record with a 3.83 ERA in 20 starts.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Faber was unable to pitch in the series due to illness, leaving manager Kid Gleason with three starting pitchers.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] However, all was not well in the White Sox camp.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In contrast to the White Sox, the 1919 Cincinnati Reds were upstarts.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] They had finished no higher than third since 1900, and then only twice, before winning the National League (NL) pennant handily in 1919.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The Reds' greatest star was center fielder Edd Roush, who led the league in hitting at .321 and, like the White Sox's Jackson, was in the top five of their respective leagues in most important hitting categories.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Third baseman Heinie Groh was the other great hitter on the team at .310 with a .392 on-base percentage and 79 runs scored.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Slick-fielding first baseman Jake Daubert, a two-time National League batting champion with Brooklyn earlier in the decade, also scored 79 runs and hit .276, while catcher Ivey Wingo hit .273.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The rest of the team was unheralded, including second baseman Morrie Rath, a .264 hitter with no power but a good on-base percentage, and shortstop Larry Kopf, a .270 singles hitter.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The corner outfielders were decidedly weaker hitters, with former Phillies star left fielder Sherry Magee's .215 in 56 games and right fielder Earle "Greasy" Neale's .242 with little power.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] This would prompt Moran to start rookie Pat Duncan in left field in the 1919 series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] However, the Reds had a strong pitching rotation.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The team's big three included Hod Eller (20–9, 2.39), Dutch Ruether (19–6, 1.82) and Slim Sallee (21–7, 2.06), all among the league leaders in various categories.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] They were backed by three other pitchers who were almost as successful: Jimmy Ring at only 10–9 but 2.26, Ray Fisher at 14–5 and 2.17 with five shutouts, and Cuban Dolf Luque at 10–3 and 2.63, former and future Giant who would win the last game of the 1933 World Series in long relief for New York.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The conspiring players on the White Sox got an unexpected assist when a flu-stricken Faber was left off the World Series roster.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Indeed, years later, catcher Schalk said that had Faber been healthy, there never would have been a fix (since he almost certainly would have gotten starts that went to Cicotte or Williams).
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Despite their many wins on the field, the Sox were an unhappy team.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Many observers blame their attitude on Comiskey's stinginess, despite the fact that the 1919 White Sox payroll was third highest in the AL, behind only Boston and New York.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Stories about the scandal have usually included Comiskey in its gallery of subsidiary villains, focusing in particular on his intentions regarding a clause in Cicotte's contract that would have paid the knuckleballer an additional $10,000 bonus for winning thirty games.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] According to Eliot Asinof's account of the events, *Eight Men Out*, Cicotte was "rested" for the season's final two weeks after reaching his 29th win presumably to deny him the bonus, but the truth may be more complex.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Cicotte won his 29th game on September 19, had an ineffective start on September 24 and was pulled after a few innings in a tuneup on the season's final day, September 28 (three days before the World Series opener).
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In addition, Cicotte reportedly agreed to the fix the same day he won his 29th game before he could have known of any efforts to deny him a chance to win his 30th.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The story was probably true with regard to the 1917 season, however, when Cicotte won 28 games and hurled the White Sox to the championship.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The first game began at 3 pm at Cincinnati's Redland Field, with 30,511 fans in the stands and ticket scalpers outside the park raking in at least $50 per ticket.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Chicago failed to score in the top of the first.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, Cicotte (who was paid his $10,000 the night before the series began) took the mound and hit the leadoff hitter (and former teammate), Morrie Rath, in the back with his second pitch, a prearranged signal to Arnold Rothstein that the fix was on.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Even so, the game remained close for a while, due in part to some excellent defense from the conspirators, seeking to deflect suspicion from themselves.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In the fourth, however, Cicotte "went haywire" (again according to Meany, *op. cit.*), allowing a number of hits in succession climaxed by a two-out triple to the opposing pitcher, as the Reds scored five times to break a 1–1 tie.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Cicotte was relieved at that point, but the damage was done and the Reds went on to add three more runs in later innings and win 9–1.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Sportswriters thought that a bad throw by Cicotte to Risberg in the fourth inning, which prevented a possible double play, was suspicious.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] By that evening, there already were signs that things were going wrong.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Only Cicotte, who had shrewdly demanded his $10,000 in advance, had been paid.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] "Sleepy" Bill Burns and Maharg met with Abe Attell, the former world boxing champ and Rothstein's intermediary, but he withheld the next installment ($20,000) nonetheless to bet on the next game.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The next morning Gandil met Attell and again demanded money, but again to no avail.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Although they had not received their money, the players were still willing to go through with the fix.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] "Lefty" Williams, the starting pitcher in Game 2, was not going to be as obvious as Cicotte.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] After a shaky start, he pitched well until the fourth inning, when he walked three and gave up as many runs.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] After that he became virtually unhittable again, giving up only one more run; but lack of clutch hitting, with Gandil a particularly guilty party, led to a 4–2 White Sox loss.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Attell was still in no mood to pay up afterwards, but Burns managed to get hold of $10,000 and gave it to Gandil, who distributed it among the conspirators.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The teams headed northwest to Comiskey Park in Chicago for Game 3 the next day, with no days off for travel in this Series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Rookie pitcher Dickey Kerr, the Game 3 starter for the Sox, was not in on the fix.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The original plan was for the conspirators, who disliked Kerr, to lose this game, but by now dissent among the players meant that the plan was in disarray.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Burns still had faith and gathered the last of his resources to bet on Cincinnati.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] It was a decision that would leave him broke, as Chicago scored early—with Gandil himself driving in two runs—and Kerr was masterful, holding the Reds to three hits in a 3–0 complete game shutout.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Cicotte took the mound again for Game 4, and was determined not to look as bad as he had in Game 1.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] For the first four innings, he and Reds pitcher Jimmy Ring matched zeroes.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] With one out in the fifth, Cicotte fielded a slow roller by Pat Duncan but threw wildly to first for a two-base error.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The next man up, Larry Kopf, singled to left; Cicotte cut off the throw from Jackson and fumbled the ball, allowing Duncan to score.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The home crowd was stunned by the veteran pitcher's obvious mistake.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Cicotte then surrendered a double to Greasy Neale which scored Kopf to make it 2–0; this was enough of a lead for Ring, who hurled a three-hit shutout of his own, matching Kerr's in Game 3.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] After the game "Sport" Sullivan came through with $20,000 for the players, which Gandil split equally among Risberg, Felsch, and Williams, who was due to start Game 5 the next day.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Both starters, Williams and Cincinnati's Hod Eller, pitched excellently at first, with neither allowing a runner past first until the top of the sixth, when Eller himself hit a blooper that fell between Felsch and Jackson.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Felsch's throw was offline, sending Eller all the way to third.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Leadoff hitter Morrie Rath then singled over the drawn-in infield, scoring Eller.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Heinie Groh walked before Edd Roush's double—the result of more doubtful defense from Felsch—brought home two more runs, with Roush scoring shortly thereafter.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Eller pitched well enough (he struck out nine batters, including a then-World Series record six in a row, since tied by Moe Drabowsky in the 1966 World Series opener) for the four runs to stand up, and the Reds were only one game away from their first world championship.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The Series reverted to Cincinnati for Game 6.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, starting for the White Sox, was less dominant than in Game 3.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Aided by three White Sox errors, the Reds jumped out to a 4–0 lead before Chicago fought back, tying the game at 4–4 in the sixth, which remained the score into extra innings.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In the top of the tenth, Gandil drove in Weaver to make it 5–4, and Kerr closed it out to record his — and Chicago's — second win.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Despite the rumors already circulating about Cicotte's erratic performances in Games 1 and 4, White Sox manager Kid Gleason showed faith in his ace for Game 7.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] This time, the knuckleballer did not let him down.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Chicago scored early and, for once, it was Cincinnati that committed errors.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The Reds threatened only briefly in the sixth before losing 4–1, and suddenly the Series was relatively close again.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] This marked the only time in World Series history that the winner of Game 7 did not ultimately go on to win the series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] This did not go unnoticed by Sullivan and Rothstein, who were suddenly worried.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Before the Series started, the Sox had been strong favorites and few doubted they could win two games in a row—presuming that they were *trying* to win.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Rothstein had been too smart to bet on individual games, but had $270,000 riding on Cincinnati to win the Series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The night before Game 8, Williams—the scheduled starter—was supposedly visited by an associate of Sullivan's known as Harry F.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] He left no doubt that if Williams failed to blow the game in the first inning, he and his wife would be in serious danger.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Chicago wouldn't see another Game 7 for over a century.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Whatever Williams had been told made its impression.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] In the first, throwing nothing but mediocre fastballs, he gave up four straight one-out hits for three runs before Gleason relieved him with "Big" Bill James, who allowed one of Williams' baserunners to score.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] James continued ineffective and, although the Sox rallied in the eighth, the Reds came away with a 10–5 victory for a five-games-to-three Series win.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Jackson hit the only homer of the Series in the third inning after the Reds had built a 5–0 lead.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Immediately after the Series ended, rumors were rife from coast to coast that the games had been thrown.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Journalist Hugh Fullerton of the *Chicago Herald and Examiner*, disgusted by the display of ineptitude with which the White Sox had "thrown" the series, wrote that no World Series should ever be played again.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Jackson led all players with his .375 average.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Some believed that most of his offensive potency came in games that were not fixed and/or when the game seemed out of reach.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] He hit the Series' lone home run in the eighth and final game, a solo shot in the third inning, by which time the Reds were already ahead 5–0.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] His five hits with runners in scoring position came in: Game 6, sixth inning with Kerr pitching; Game 7, first and third innings; Game 8, two in the four-run eighth.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] Shoeless Joe had 12 hits overall, a World Series record at that time and tied for the most in an eight-game series.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The Reds would make their next World Series appearance two decades later, but were swept by the New York Yankees, becoming the last victim of a Yankees dynasty of four straight championships from 1936 to 1939.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] They would win their next championship in 1940 over the Detroit Tigers in seven games after being nine outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:1919-world-series/1919-world-series] The scandal cast a shadow that lasted decades.
